    longDescription: "You don't need a hurricane to suffer significant wind damage to your roof. Charleston regularly experiences severe thunderstorms with straight-line winds exceeding 60 mph, nor'easters that batter the coast for days, and microbursts that can produce localized winds over 100 mph. Even sustained winds of 45-50 mph — common during our spring and fall storm seasons — can lift shingles, tear off ridge caps, and compromise flashing around chimneys and vents.\n\nWind damage is particularly insidious because it often starts small and worsens over time. A single lifted shingle tab creates a point where wind can get underneath and peel back entire sections. Compromised flashing allows water to penetrate behind the roofing material where it's invisible from the ground. By the time you notice a leak inside your home, the underlying damage may be extensive.\n\nOur wind damage repair process starts with a thorough inspection — both from the ground using binoculars and on the roof itself. We check every vulnerable point: ridge caps, hip caps, rake edges, valleys, pipe boots, and all flashing transitions. We document everything with photos and measurements for your insurance claim, then provide a detailed repair plan.\n\nFor minor wind damage, we can often complete repairs the same day. For more extensive damage, we'll install temporary protection while we source matching materials and schedule the full repair. Our goal is always to restore your roof to its pre-storm condition using manufacturer-approved materials and installation methods.",
