    description: "Comprehensive water damage restoration for roofing systems compromised by flooding, storm surge, or prolonged water exposure in the Charleston Lowcountry.",
    longDescription: "Charleston's low elevation and proximity to the coast make it uniquely vulnerable to water damage from multiple sources — storm surge during hurricanes, tidal flooding during king tides, flash flooding from heavy rainfall, and the persistent moisture that comes with living at sea level in a subtropical climate. When water reaches your roof system — whether from above through storm damage or from below through flooding — the consequences can be severe and long-lasting.\n\nWater damage to roofing systems goes far beyond what's visible on the surface. When water penetrates the roof deck, it saturates the plywood or OSB sheathing, soaks into insulation, and creates the perfect environment for mold and rot. In Charleston's warm, humid climate, mold can begin growing within 24-48 hours of water exposure and can spread rapidly through your attic and into living spaces.\n\nFlood damage presents additional challenges. When floodwater reaches the attic or roof structure — as can happen during major storm surge events — it introduces contaminants, sediment, and bacteria that require specialized cleanup. Saturated roof decking may need to be replaced entirely, and all insulation in contact with floodwater must be removed and replaced.\n\nOur water damage restoration process begins with moisture mapping — using specialized equipment to identify exactly where water has penetrated and how far it has spread. We then develop a remediation plan that addresses both immediate water removal and long-term restoration. This may include controlled demolition of damaged materials, professional drying with industrial dehumidifiers, mold remediation, structural repair, and re-roofing.\n\nWe coordinate with water damage restoration specialists, mold remediation companies, and your insurance company to ensure comprehensive restoration of your home.",
